ficient. They demonstrate the ability of their planning procedure to yield equitable and efficient outcomes even in the context of externalities and public goods and its power to stimulate rather than subvert participatory impulses. Also included is a discussion of information management and how simulation experiments can substantiate the feasibility of their model.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCentral planning. 0aEconomics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh  aAllocation Organization.  aAllocation.  aAmadeus.  aBalance in Practice.  aCentral Planning.  aChoice of Technology.  aConstraints.  aConsumption Institutions.  aConverging to a Plan.  aDiversity.  aEquity Versus Efficiency.  aEquity.  aHierarchical Production.  aModeling Production.  aParticipatory Planning.  aPreliminary Insights.  aSimulation Methodology.  aThe Logic of Power.  aValuative Criteria.  aWelfare Economics.  aWork Organization.1 aHahnel, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691216003zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691216003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691216003.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK